1. Singleton Pattern
Singleton Pattern ensures that only one object of a class is created throughout the application.
It provides a global access point to that object.
It is useful when multiple objects can cause inconsistency.
This pattern saves memory and controls resource usage.
Commonly used for configuration, logging, and cache management.

Simple Java Code
public class SingleTon {
    private SingleTon(){}

    private static SingleTon instance;

    public static SingleTon getInstance(){
        if(instance==null){
            instance=new SingleTon();
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SingleTon obj1=SingleTon.getInstance();
        SingleTon obj2=SingleTon.getInstance();

        System.out.println(obj1.equals(obj2));

        System.out.println(obj1==obj2);
    }
}

2. Factory Method Pattern
Factory Method Pattern creates objects through a factory class instead of creating them directly using new.
The client only requests an object, and the factory decides which object to create.
This reduces dependency between classes and makes the code easy to maintain.
New object types can be added without changing the client code.

Without Factory Pattern
Suppose you have a payment application.

Payment payment = new UpiPayment();
payment.pay();

Tomorrow the user wants to pay using a Card:
Payment payment = new CardPayment();
payment.pay();

Now the client code needs to know:
Which class to create?
When to create UpiPayment?
When to create CardPayment?

This creates dependency on concrete classes.

With Factory Pattern
Client simply says:
Payment payment = PaymentFactory.getPayment("UPI");
payment.pay();

The factory decides:
if(type.equals("UPI"))
    return new UpiPayment();
else
    return new CardPayment();
Now the client doesn't care which object is created.

Simple java code
  interface payment{
      void pay();
  }

  class UPIPayment implements payment{

      @Override
      public void pay() {
          System.out.println("paid using UPI");
      }
  }

  class CreditCard implements payment{
      @Override
      public void pay(){
          System.out.println("Paid using CreditCard");
      }
  }

  class NetBanking implements payment{
      @Override
      public void pay(){
          System.out.println("Paid using NetBanking");
      }
  }

  class FactoryClass{
      public static payment getPayment(String mode) {
          if(mode.equalsIgnoreCase("upi")){
              return new UPIPayment();
          } else if (mode.equalsIgnoreCase("cred")) {
              return new CreditCard();
          }else if(mode.equalsIgnoreCase("netbanking")){
              return new NetBanking();
          }
          throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid payment mode");
      }
  }
  public class FactoryPattern {

      public static void main(String[] args) {
          Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);
          System.out.println("Please enter payment mode");
          String str=sc.nextLine();
          payment pay=FactoryClass.getPayment(str);
          pay.pay();
      }
  }


